==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

Various explanations exist.

In {{w|oracle bone script}} there were two primary forms:

* ({{zh-l|*𬙜}} = {{l|mul|⿱罒矢}}) {{Han compound|目|矢|t1=eye|t2=arrow|ls=ic}}, possibly meaning “to shoot” or “to see”.
* ({{l|mul|⿱㚔廾}} or {{l|mul|⿱㚔𠬜}}) {{Han compound|㚔|廾|t1=handcuffs|t2=|ls=ic}} or {{l|mul|𠬜}} (“pair of hands”) on each side, likely denoting “to release” (now written {{l|mul|釋}}), especially considering the position of hands in {{l|mul|𠬜}} are facing away the handcuffs ([[#Chineserefs|Qiu, 1993]]; [[#Chineserefs|Chen, 2015]]).

Commonly used in bronze inscriptions to denote  “to pick” (now written {{l|mul|擇}}) (ibid.), as {{l|mul|擇}} (“to pick”) and {{l|mul|釋}} (“to release”) are etymologically and semantically related ([[#Chineserefs|Yu and Yang, 2023]] citing Liu, 2014). To the latter form, the composition {{l|mul|𢍰}} with an eye ({{l|mul|目}}) added appeared in as late as Eastern Zhou bronze inscriptions. It probably serves to fortify the denotion of picking (with eyes) ([[#Chineserefs|Chang, 2016]]; [[#Chineserefs|Yu and Yang, 2023]]). In the same period, a composition with hand omitted appeared, giving rise to the current glyph {{Han compound|目|㚔|t1=eye|t2=handcuff}} (ibid.).

